The NOAA Coastal Services Center's Legislative Atlas is a regional geographic information system (GIS) that provides spatial data for state and federal coastal and ocean management laws and the jurisdictional boundaries of management agencies. There are a growing number of regional collaborations among federal, state, and local agencies to address coastal management issues that cut across existing political and jurisdictional boundaries. To support regional management efforts, the Coastal Services Center has developed geographic representations of key state and federal legislation and the jurisdictional boundaries of state and federal management agencies.
The Legislative Atlas allows users to identify what coastal and ocean laws apply at specific locations and to visualize relationships between the management framework and the natural and socio-economic resources in a region. This dataset represents the jurisdictional boundaries of the Fishery Management Councils' regions. THE SPATIAL REPRESENTATIONS OF LEGISLATION AND AGENCY JURISDICTIONS ARE BASED ON INTERPRETATION OF AVAILABLE INFORMATION AND SHOULD NOT BE CONSTRUED AS LEGALLY BINDING. These data are regional in scale (1:100,000) and are intended for regional coastal and ocean planning purposes. Not for use for scales greater than 1:100,000.

As interpreted from the U.S. code, the regulatory authority of the Fishery Management Councils applies to U.S. federal waters, extending from the Federal-State boundary to the seaward extent of the U.S. Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ). The Fishery Management Councils' jurisdictional boundaries were developed from two existing data sets: (1) the Federal-State boundary for the continental U.S. distributed by the Minerals Management Service (http://www.mms.gov/ld/Maps.htm) and (2) the EEZ of the U.S. distributed by NOAA's Office of Coast Survey (http://nauticalcharts.noaa.gov/csdl/EEZ.HTM). The Federal-State shapefile was downloaded from MMS for each region (Atlantic, Gulf, and Pacific) and merged into one shapefile after reprojecting the Gulf Federal-State shapefile from NAD27 to NAD83. Lateral boundaries were created between Fishery Managment Council regions (as described at http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/councils.htm), extending from the Federal-State line to the seaward extent of the EEZ. These lateral boundaries were based on best available information, but should not be interpreted as official boundaries. The lateral boundary polylines and Federal-state polylines were combined with the shapefiles representing the EEZ for the continental U.S. in the Features to Polygon tool in ArcGIS to create a single polygon shapefile for the Fishery Management Council regions.
